<h2 class="text-center my-5">The Importance of the Jedi Pillars</h2>
<p>The three pillars of the Jedi stand as the foundation of the order, as do the initiates who study them. Once they reach the age of 12, or equivalent age, they must take the Initiate Trials, where they must show complete understanding of the three pillars of the Jedi. This test includes a theoretical portion to determine their competence in academics, a lightsaber combat portion, and a portion on their connection of the Force. Many students do fail these trials, despite how early they happen in a Jedi's lifetime.</p>

<p>If however they do pass, then they will become Padawan learners.</p>

<p>But they are not guaranteed to become apprentices. Jedi Padawans must, in some way, gain the attention of a Jedi Knight or Master who is looking for an apprentice. There are some ways available within the temple where one can apply for and find apprenticeship. Including the annual lightsaber tournament, applying with the reassignment council, or talking to past instructors about finding an apprenticeship. But sometimes all you got to do is stick your neck out there and talk to other knights and masters within the order. This can prove a challenge enough, and can see some padawans never become apprentices.</p>

<p>If however you do become an apprentice, then you have a greater challenge ahead of you, your duty as a Jedi.</p>

<p>Padawans are expected to aid, and keep up with their masters who will outrank them in everyway. They are expected to learn all they can from their masters and their experience in the field. They are expected not only to do all of these things, but also do their duty as a Jedi in the field, this means being the Guardian the people expect them to be. It is here where not only padawans will fail, but will sometimes meet their end.</p>

<p>But if they do succeed, then they will find one of the most enriching experience of their lives, and their most closest friend in their master, who will share those feelings as he will have learned a thing or two from the apprentice.</p>
