<h2 class="text-center my-5">But then comes the last trials: The Jedi Knight Trials.</h2>
<div class="row text-center mb-5">
	<div class="col">
		<img src="~/images/jedi-trials.png" class="img-fluid" alt="Image depicting five tenents of the Jedi trials" />
	</div>
</div>
<p>There five trials in total to test different aspects of what it takes to be a Jedi Knight. Those trials include: the trial of courage, the trial of flesh, the trial of spirit, the trial of wisdom, and the trial of skill. Each trial was different for each student, each one being tailored for particular challenges that they would have to face. Oftentimes, the trials would specifically test their specific weaknesses in each area, and sometimes the trials would happen without the student even realizing it, sometimes disguised as a mission, or normal lesson.</p>
<ol>
	<li>The Trial of Skill. The trial of skill was the me most grueling physical challenge padawans would ever had to face as students. The trial tested not only their skill with a lightsaber, but also their physical endurance, their creativity, and their ability to use the Force in combat. The trial was sometimes conducted by the student fighting a Jedi Master, multiple warriors one after another, two on one fights, or fighting holographic projections of Sith Lords.</li>
	<li>The Trial of Flesh. This trial tested the students ability to overcome great pain. In the early days of the Jedi Order, some students were even shot by blasters on the lowest setting with a sustained beam for literally hours (In the time of Kenobi and Yoda, such practice was considered barbaric). In the modern times, the test determines a Jedi’s ability to handle deep emotional pain and loss. Oftentimes, a pupil would never see their master again, and must part ways permanently, this separation was often part of the Trial of Flesh.</li>
	<li>The Trial of Courage. The Jedi must be able to stand in the face of fear, and overcome that fear to do what is necessary. This test often puts students in combat against a horrible foe that they would have no hope of defeating. Though many students end up rushing and defeating the foe, they end up failing anyway, because recklessness is not the same thing as courage.</li>
	<li>The Trial of Wisdom. This was the most recent trial instituted in the Jedi Order. The reason for this was because the original four trials were producing competent Jedi, but however those Jedi often fell to the cunning tricks of hutt crime lord. This Trial would include all sorts of puzzles and riddles, and most times, a student discovering they were even facing this trial was part of their test.</li>
	<li>The Trial of Spirit. Also known as “Facing the Mirror”, this is considered to be the hardest trial of all. To pass this trial, one must look deep inside themselves, and confront that which they have hidden all their lives: their greatest fears, shame, regrets, and inner darkness. Once this darkness is found, it must be confronted, defeated, and accepted; not many have the fortitude to face such a challenge.Many who have failed this test have literally gone mad, but however, this test is as difficult as it is critical to becoming a Jedi.</li>
</ol>

<p>Failure in any one trial is considered a failure in all, but if you manage to make it all the way here, than congratulations, you will become a Jedi Knight of the Republic. Now you will be free to fulfill your duty to everyone in the Galaxy, however you see fit. With this title comes many responsibilities and privileges, all of which, have been greatly earned.</p>